{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_hodag_ver01/data/sn86086586/00414214496/1908011701/0561.xml":{"full_text":"VOLUM-K 34.\nBusiness Directory.\nHENRY JOHNSON,\nFire, Tornado, Life and Accident\nInsurance,\nBDGERTON, WISCONSIN.\nJSP-Offlcein Schineling Block.\nW. T. POMEROY CO.,\nDealers in and packers of\nLeaf Tobacco,\nEdgerton, Wisconsin.\nO. G. HANSEN. C. H. HANSEN\nHANSEN BROS.,\n(Successors to O. G. Hansen)\nDealers in\nLeaf Tobacco,\nBDGERTON' WIS.\nANDREW JENSON SONS,\nPackers of and Dealers in\nLeaf Tobacco,\nEDGERTON, WISCONSIN.\nC. E. SWEENEY.\nDEALER IN\nLeaf Tobacco\nEDGERTON, WISCONSIN\nO. LEE-\nDealer in am. Packer of\nLeaf Tobacco,\nSTOUGHTON, WISCONSIN.\nH. R. POMEROY\nPACKER OF\nLEAF TOBACCO\nWarehouse at Soldiers Grove.\nCommission Business Solicited.\nGAYS MILLS. WIS.\nHEINRICH NEUBERGER\nEXPORTER\nBremen, 145 Water St.\nGermany. New York, N. Y-\nE- ROSENWALD BRO.\nSUCCESSOR TO\nE. Rosenwald Bro. and I. Bijur Son,\nPACKERS OF\nLeaf Tobacco,\n145 Water Street,\nNew York City.\nS. C. CHAMBERS,\nDEALER IN AND PACKER OF\nLeaf Tobacco,\nMILTON JUNCTION. WIS.\nPAMPERIN LEAF TOBACCO CO.,\nPackers Exclusively of\nNORTHERN GROWN\nWisconsin Leaf.\nLa Crosse, Wis.\nNorthern Wisconsin\nLeaf Tobacco Cos.\nPackers of and Dealers exclusively iu\nNorthern Grown Wisconsin Tobacco\nLaCrosse, Wisconsin.\nFRED. SCHNATBEL,\n(formerly of ruscher CO.)\nTobacco Inspector\nSTORAGE.\n149 Water Street. NEW YORK\nGEO F. McGIFFIN, Western Agt.\nPhone No. 145. Edgerton, Wis.\nTobacco Exchange Bank\nThe conservative banker in making loans must know to a cer\ntainty that his applicants or sureties are responsible and\nworthy of credit. Likewise, the prudent depositor will know\nthe character and standing of the Bank with which he deals.\nTherefore, before inviting his confidence and soliciting his pat\nronage, we beg to submit list of our director and stockholders\nDIRECTORS:\na NDREW JENSON, Pres. W. S. HEDDLES, Vice Pres.\nBtat e biederman, and. l. baboook,\nW 2 TSoci' e y-LEY, Wm. BUSSEY,\ny ALEX WHITE.\nF. W. Coon, Wm. Mclntosh E. L. Shepard\nL. C. Whittet P. N. Johnson W. S. Brown Estate\nJ. H. Ooon W. A. DeLancy O. E. Eweeney\nLars Ellickson Florence Child Jake Bady\nL. H. Towne J. M. Hixon L. J. Dickinson\nHenry Johnson. T. E. Brittingham F. P. Mclntosh\nAnd. Mclntosh C. F. Mabbett E. S. Hatch\nHenrv Ebbo%t\nALWAYS SMOKE\n\u201cMc\u2019s No. 10\u201d Cigar\nand you will enjoy satisfaction. $35 per M.\nEDGERTON CIGAR GO Edgerton, Wis.\nCHAS. L. CULTON,\nLEAF TOBACCO.\nEDGERTON, WISCONSIN.\nMaGee\u2019s Improved Tobacco Case.\nThe best case made for the packing of Leaf Tobacco.\nSampling done with one half the labor and expense.\nWrite for delivered prices in car load lots.\nMaGEE BROS. Janesville Wis.\nOffice and Warehouse adjoining C., M. St. P. Passenger Station.\nFRAZIER M. DOLBEER. GEORGE F. SECOR, Special.\nOriginal \u201cLINDE\u201d New York Seed Leaf Tobacco Inspection,\nESTABLISHED IN 1864.\nF. C. LINDE, HAMILTON CO.\nTobacco Inspectors, Weighers Warehousemen.\n3ice, 180 Pearl St. New York City. Branches In ail of the principal tobacco districts\nA. H. CLARKE, Special Agent, Edgerton, Wis. Badger \u2019Phone No. 71\nCOLSON C. HAMILTON,\nFormerly of C. E. HAMILTON FRANK P. WISEBURN,\nF. C. Lind a, Hamilton Cos. LOUIS BUHLE\nFormerly with F. C. Linde, Hamilton Cos.\nC. C. HAMILTON CO.,\nTobacco Inpsectors, Warehousemen, Weighers.\nMalnOfftce\u2014B4-85 South Street, New York.\nTHOS. B. EARLE, Agent, Edgerton, Wis. Telephone No, 23\nK __\nB. MEDDLES\nDEALER IN\nj\u2014nrcDESAcrczciD,\nJANESVILLE. WISCONSIN.\nKO. 6 SOUTH ADAMS\nGREENS\u2019 TOBACCO CO.,\nDealers in Leaf Tobacco,!\nWarehouses at Janesville, Milton and Brooklyn, Wis.\nSTORAGE CAPACITY, 15,000 OASES\nJanesville, Wisconsin.\nGARY TOBACCO CO.\nDEALERS IN\nLeaf Tobacco,\nEdgerton, Wisconsin.\nBDGERTON, WISCONSIN, FRIDAY, JANUARY 17. 1908.\nA. N. JONES,\nDEALER IN\nAND PACKER OF\nLeaf Tobacco.\n118,120, 122 N. Main\nand Pease Court,\nJanesville. Wisconsin.\nCampbell-Peterson Tobacco Co*,\nDealers in and Packers of\nLeaf Tobacco,\nOrfordville, Wisconsin.\nNOTE BOOK SKETCHES\nThe annual convention of the Wiscon\nsin Tobacco Growers and Dealers\u2019 asso\nciation will probably be held at Janes\nville about the middle of February in\nconnection with a tobacco institute held\nunder the auspices of the state depart\nment of farmers\u2019 institutes. The state\nforce of lecturers will be drawn upon for\na portion of the program and the asso\nciation officers will co-operate in making\nthe coming meeting one of especial in\nterest to all engaged in this industry.\nAt a meeting of the diredtors Saturday\nplans were discussed and the program\npartly mapped out for the coming con\nvention. The usual prizes for the best\nsamples of last season\u2019s crop will be\nhung up for competition. Full particu\nlars of the dates and program will be\npublished in due time.\nFor more than two hours Judge Joel\nT. Fort, a clever orator from Tennessee,\nlambasted the tobacco trust before an\naudience of farmers that filled Royal\nhall to overflowing last Friday afternoon.\nWhile the audience cheered at his rail\nlery, Judge Fort hammered away at the\ntrust from all sides until it was down\nand out and then danced upon its pros\ntrate form, and then some people won\ndered what it was all about. The Judge\nmakes a mistake when he accuses the\nAmerican Tobacco Cos. of controlling Jhe\ntobacco markets of Wisconsin. He\nmakes another mistake when he thinks\nthe tobacco growers need the protection\nof soch organizations as he suggests.\nThe tobacco growers of Wisconsin are\ntoo intelligent, too prosperous, too con\ntented and tob independent to turn their\nproduct over to any pool or organization\nto market. He makes a fatal mistake\nwhen he attempts to justify (as we fear\ned he would) the mob rule, murder and\nincendiarism pursued by the Kentucky\ntobacco growers. Such talk can never\nbe popular in Wisconsin. It isn\u2019t going\nto >e popular long in Kentucky if Gov.\nWillson has his way.\nThe Reporter would be negligent if it\npermitted Judge Fort to get away with\nout calling him to account for these\nthings.\nAfter all, tobacco growers are not\nwiser than the rest of mankind\u2014we\nmean those in Wisconsin. They have\nformed a branch of what they call the\nSociety of Equity, which, separated from\nits resounding name, means an attempt\nto compel buyers to pay more for their\ncrops than the latter believe they are\nworth. Coming, as this attempt does,\nafter the prices of last year, we cannot\nbut think the effort a very unwise one.\nMeetings have been held all over the\nstate and many farmers have pledged\nthat all the tobacco not sold by Jan\nuary 15,1908, will be assorted, cased and\nplaced in a \u201cpool,\u201d to be sold for not less\nthan the prices agreed upon at a recent\nstate convention of tobacco growers. It\nwill be remembered that during the fall\nand winter of 1906-07 the same condi\ntions that prevailed here in Pennsyl\nvania also prevailed in Wisconsin. In\nsome way the buyers were swept off\ntheir feet in their wild efforts to get\ntheir usual supplies, and the result was\nthat a price much in excess of that or\ndinarily prevailing was paid for the crop.\nAs the buyers have not turned out this\nfall and are not tumbling over each oth\ner to get a few cases of Wisconsin bind\ners at prices beyond their worth the\ngrowers have now entered into a trust\nto compel the manufacturers to pay the\nprices demanded. We have no belief,\nwhatever, that the proposed undertak\ning will prove successful. Trade in to\nbacco has never been duller the country\nover than it is today. The report of the\nInternal Revenue department in Decem\nber last shows that less cigar tobacco\nwas used up by manufacturers than in\nany month during the past eight years.\nThat condition of things may continue\nor it may improve, but as things are to\nday what prospect is there that the\nWisconsin growers can compel the out\nside world to buy their binders at 15\ncents and the lower grades that usually\nsell at 6 and 7 cents at 12% cents? If\nthey do put their crops into a pool and\nwait for 15 ceut buyers, we predict that\nif the trust docs not bust, as we believe\nit will, it will be a very cold and stormy\nwait before they get the money for their\ncrons. It is idle to say the manufactur\ners \"\u201cmust have it.\u201d We beard that song\nfor the past eighteen months, and it\nnever came true. The 1906 crop is still\non hand, and, as many cigar factories all\nover the country are closing for the time\nbeing, the demand will, of necessity, be\neven lighter than it has been during the\npast six months. The fact is, when any\narticle, through whatever circumstance,\ngoes beyond its real value, there is\nbound to come along a reaction that will\ncarry prices just as far in the other di\nrection. And when any set of men set\nto work to bid defiance to these natural\nlaws of supply and demand, and insist\nthey shall be paid more for their pro\nducts than the situation will warrant,\nthere will be trouble. So, we believe,\nour Wisconsin friends will find it, and\nfind it when it is too late. Wisconsin\nbinders will bring 15 cents in the mar\nket when somebody is ready to pay that\nprice for them, and not before, even\nthough every leaf of tobacco grown in\nthat state last year is put into the pool.\nIf her farmers do not believe it oow they\nwill a year hence.\u2014Lancaster New Era.\nWl\u00dfColi\u00dflft TOBACCO MARKET\nEdokrton, Wis.. Jan. 17, 1908. j\nWhile buyers are picking up a few\ncrops of \u2019O7 leaf, there is still absent the\nindications of a general movement that\nought to be due at this time of the year.\nThe prices paid seem low enough to en\ncourage trading if there were not some\nbetter reasons why the movement is not\nunder way. We hear a few sales were\nmade to Janesville buyers in the Orford\nville district this week at figures around\n8 cents, and further transactions reach\ning us are:\nHanson Bros., 4a at 9&2c.\nOle Bakken, 2a at B&2c.\nS. A. Hoffiand, 7a at B&2c.\nT. Melheim, 6a at 7&2c.\nJulius Sommerfeldt, 2a at 6&2c.\nThe new crop is being handled in\nthree warehouses of this market in a\nlimited way and the result of the grad\ning is being watched with considerable\ninterest as a guide for future business.\nThe old leaf market is a good deal of a\ndeadlock. Some 1906 goods might be\nmoved if packers were willing to accept\nlosses but as yet they are not ready to\ndo so, and thus matters will stand until\nparty makes a concession. We\nlearn a few hundred cases of \u2019OS goods\nwere sold by a Janesville packer to an\neastern house this week.\nThe shipments out of storage continue\nlight, probably 400 cs for the week to all\npoints from this market.\nNew fork.\nNew York, Jan. 11,1908\nBusiness in the leaf market has not\nyet opened to any extent. This is being\nchiefly accounted for by the fact that\nmost factories are still inoperative, part\nly because of inventory taking and partly\nbecause of the lack of sufficient orders.\nWhat little business is being done is in\nsmall quantities to supply an occasional\nimmediate want. Some time is likely to\nelapse beiore factories will resume a\nnormal Sctivity and then the leaf mar\nket will again become a centre of hustle\nand bargain.\nThe usual post-holiday period of dull\nness prevails in the local cigar manu\nfacturing industry. Practically no sales\nmen are out on the road and manufac\nturers are making little effort to secure\ntrade. In |he meantime manufacturers\nhave been kept busy taking the annual\ninventory and a number of the factories\nwere closed for a day or two. Or the\nwhole the showing is not as bad as was\nexpected. It is true that the statistics\ncompiled show a decrease in the output\nof the Metropolitan district of 114,377,332\nas compared with 1906. Fully 85 per\ncent, of this falling off, however, took\nplace during the last quarter of the year,\nand may in a large measure be put down\nto the financial panic, a more or less ac\ncidental condition, which, there is rea\nson to hope, will not recur.\u2014Journal.\nNew York, Jan. 8,1908\nThe manufacturers have begun to\nnibble at the market offerings, but as\nyet no transactions of large importance\nhave been recorded. Inquiries have\nbeen numerous, however, and during the\npast week no day has passed without\nmore or less business being done. Busi\nness has been confined chiefly to Penn\nsylvania, Wisconsin and Zimmer Span\nish tobacco. Packers feel considerably\nencouraged over the prospects, particu\nlarly In view of the fact that the holiday\ntrade of cigar dealers is reported to have\nbeen of unexpectedly large proportions.\nKnowing that for the past few months\nthe cigar-jobbing firms and retailers\nhave been operating with the smallest\npossible margin of stocks, leaf dealers\nargue that the business they will\nthe manufacturers will compel the lay\ning in of heavy stocks of tobacco by the\nlatter class, especially as the manufact\nurers have not bought heavily for some\ntime past.\nSumatra. \u2014While few sales have been\nreported, it may be said that during the\npast week there has been more inquiry\nfor Sumatra than is usual for this time\nof the year.\nHavana. Dealers specializing this\ntype of tobacco report a few transactions\nduring the past week, some of the sales\nbeing of Vuelta, but more being of Par\ntido Numerous inquiries have been\nmade regarding factory types, and the\ndealers expect an expansion of business\nin the next few weeks.\u2014Leaf.\nConnecticut V'alley Tobacco Market.\nIn the line of news in the tobacco\nworld there is very little, and that little\nnot the kind to make a correspondent\nproud to report. About all is the draw\ning of tobacco to the assorting shops.\nThis is better than to 9ee the tobacco\nlying in the bundle all winter, and per\nhaps later. To draw the crop carries on\nits face a determination to do something\nwith the tobacco now that it has ben\nraised and shed cured.\nBut I would much rather see each\ngrower take this assorting business into\nhis own hands. He is tne only proper\nperson to handle his own growing and if\nhe has not the suitable room to assort in\nlet him club witb uis neighbor, and the\ntwo work together, allowing each grower\nto superintend assorting his own crop.\nOur correspondents report as follows:\nWethersfield, Ct.: \u201cThe rainy weather\nhas enabled the farmers to take their to\nbacco nearly all from the poles and 9trip\nit off and put in the bundle. Very few\nbuyers around as yet.\u201d North Hatfield,\nMass \u201cNo bu>ers have been seen in\nthis vicinity during the past week. W.\nWolfram has opened his shop during the\npast week with 17 men. L. A. Crafts\nhas opened his shop employing 25 men\naDd boys. Leslie W. Swift has increased\nthe force at his shop to 70 men, at a\nprice of $1.50 for so. ters and about $1.25\nfor sizers.\u201d\u2014Cultivator.\nGEO. W- DOTY. ROY F. WRIGHT,\nPresident Cashier\nTHE\nFirst National\nBANK\nEdgerton, Wisconsin.\nLearn How to Save\nMoney\nIt is a duty you owe yourself. A\nbank account with this institution\nwill help you to prosper-it will\nhelp you to get ahead in the world\n\u2014it will increase your happiness.\ntjauuHHter.\nLancaster, Pa., Jan. 7,1908.\nThere is absolutely nothing new in the\nlocal leaf tobacco market. The holidays\nkept away the few would-be buyers who\nhave been hunting Lancaster with the\nexpectation of finding a packer who\nmight be induced to part with his goods\nbelow the market prices, and it would\nnot have mattered if there had been any\nvisitors. Buyers from abroad and the\nholders of the goods are dead-locked\nover prices, and there is nothing on\nwhich even to hazard a guess as to how\nlong this will last. It is a waiting per\niod now, packers waiting for customers,\nand manufacturers and out of-tovvn buy\ners waiting for a break in prices.\nThere is nothing doing in the new\ncrop, either, though the growers are now\nstripping. As there will be no buying\nof the 1907 tobacco until that of 1906\nmoves off, nothing can be said of the\nprices likely to prevail in connection\nwith the new crop.\nThe cigar industry is about as dull as\nthe leaf trade, and the manufacturers\nare waiting for the long-deferred orders\nand drop in the prices of old tobacco.\nNew Era.\nMiamisburg, 0., Jan. 7, 1908.\nLast week brought more \u201ccasing\u201d\nweather, and practically nearly all the\ntobacco has been taken down in this\nvicinity. This will give the farmers an\nopportunity to work steadily at tobacco\nstripping, and finish the job before\nspring comes.\u2014News.\nThe Kentucky Governor Takes a Hand\nThe net result of the outrages com\nmitted in the Southern tobacco sections\nare summarized in the first message of\nGov. Willson to the general assembly as\nfollows: In the meantime not a benefit\nhas resulted to the oppressed farmers\nfrom those acts of violence. Even those\nmember# of the association have their\nproperty tied up, and liberty, in places\nthreatened by these bands, is an idle\ntheory and farce. Factories and ware\nhouses, which the farmers warmly wel\ncorned, have been burned and many oth\ners closed forever. Our tobacco market\nis nearly destroyed. Large customers\nare driven elsewhere; large crops re\nmain unsold; managers who have prom\nised large prices for pooled crops have\nseen the buyers driven from the field,\nand no one can tell when the end will\ncome; but every one can see that the re\nsults up to this time are that our mar\nkets, not only for tobacco but for other\nproducts, are paralyzed and in many\ncases ruined, that in large districts the\nlaw has been wholly overthrown and the\npoor people who have no one to take\ncare of them are deprived of the protec\ntion of the laws and have lost their lib\nerty and are helpless; that thousands of\npeople wish to move out of Kentucky,\nand that the very flower of our working\npopulation wishes to leave the state, as\nthousands have done before, and that\nthe people of Kentucky have suddenly\nand squarely to face the question wheth\ner the laws of more than 2,000,000 or the\nviolence of a few hundreds shall prevail.\nCigar Production.\nThe trade will undoubtedly be grati\nfied to learn that the output of our cigar\nindustry for the year just passed, that is\n1907, in the dominating cigar manufact\nuring districts escaped the severer con\nsequences of the recent financial panic\nwith just a black eye. In spite of the\ntremendous slump in the two closing\nmonths of the >ear, November and De\ncember, the output in the leading larg\nest cigar producing and in the third\nlargest district, both located in Pennsyl\nvania, shows even an increase over the\nphenomenal record breaking output of\n1906, namely, an increase of three mil\nlions and eight hundred thousand in the\nNinth, and one of about five millions in\nthe First. The hardest hit by the panic\nwere the Metropolitan districts of New\nYork, which suffered a falling off of over\none hundred and fourteen millions. The\nnext district showing the effects of the\npanic in a severe loss is the First Ohio,\nwhose output for the year shrank fifteen\nmillions. -U. S. Tob. Journal.\nKush Tobacco to Safety.\nToba :co from all parts of the entire\nstate of Kentucky is being hurried to\nLouisville in storage warehouses, >vh- r*\nit may be insured, to escape the obcd\nlation of policies or refusal of risks\nowing to apprehension of raids 6* \u201cDight\nriders.\u201d Local insurance m->> -*y that\norders have not been reo u>d for the\ncancellation of policies on to >aceo stored\nin Louisville.\nA detail of twelve men tr< m :he First\nregiment, Kentucky National (Liard, left\nLouisville Thursday for Lebanon, in re\nsponse to orders issued by Gov. Willson,\nto protect the property of the American\nTobacco people at that place. Lebanon\nhas been threatened by \u201cnight riders.\u201d\nNUMBEB 7","height":"31416","width":"21741"}}
